==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lynx
<hw>Lynx</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>lynx</ets>, <ets>lyncis</ets>, Gr. <grk>ly`gx</grk>; akin to AS.
<ets>lox</ets>, G. <ets>luchs</ets>, prob. named from its sharp sight,
and akin to E. <ets>light</ets>. See <er>Light</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Ounce</er> an animal.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>Any one of several species of feline animals of the genus
<gen>Felis</gen>, and subgenus <gen>Lynx</gen>. They have a short tail,
and usually a pencil of hair on the tip of the ears.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 878 --></p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among the well-known species are the European lynx
(<spn>Felis borealis</spn>); the Canada lynx or loup-cervier (<spn>Felis
Canadensis</spn> syn. <spn>Lynx lynx</spn>); the bay lynx of America
(<spn>Felis rufa</spn>), and its western spotted variety (var.
<varn>maculata</varn>); and the pardine lynx (<spn>Felis pardina</spn>)
of Southern Europe.</note></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the northern
constellations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lynx-eyed</ent>⟦br⟧
